<h4>“Town Planning Scheme No. 230”: the construction of a new settlement industrial zone on the lands of Saffa</h4>

<p>The illegal settler industrial zone is announced to be built on about 318 dunums of land that are privately owned by Palestinian families from the village of Saffa. This plot of land, located south of the village, has long been threatened by Israeli settlement expansion as it was designated as “state land” by the Israeli regime in 1989 and assigned 'Area C' by the Oslo Accords.
</p>

<p>On the 21st of June 2016, the director of planning at the Israeli Ministry of Finance deposited the Town Planning Scheme (TPS) No. 230, stating the establishment of an industrial zone that will be operated by the nearby Modi’in Illit settlement bloc (ARIJ, 2016). While Saffa is the most impacted, farmer families from the nearby villages of Beit Sira and Beit Ur At Tahta will also have their lands confiscated. About three weeks ago, the Israeli authorities decided to move forward with the appropriation of this plot of land and began the construction of the industrial zone on Palestinian land.
</p>

<p>While stepping on Palestinians' land, property and socio-economic rights and negatively impacting the development of neighboring indigenous communities, the Israeli industrial zone will benefit the nearby illegal Israeli settlements located on the other side of the apartheid wall, whose establishment already resulted in the seizure of much of the lands of Saffa in the 2000s.</p>

